Reviews:
[{'author_name': 'Kim Bucholtz', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/101983087179174182684/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/AATXAJx411SVCEC8Kkm_wVHiA8So6mXRDkvb7aq1Qudh=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': '3 months ago', 'text': 'I received a Bear Totem by Artist, Cecilia Adams as a gift for 40 years of working for the same non-profit organization. I love and appreciate  the First Nations culture and art!
My favorite gallery to purchase their work is Douglas Reynolds! They have a beautiful assortment of quality pieces that will fill your life and home with joy and appreciation of First Nations work.
The staff is very knowledgeable and helpful in helping you choose your treasure.
I have since moved to California but have not forgotten this gallery.
A Haida bracelet was on my Holiday wishlist and my husband bought it last week!
It arrived yesterday in the mail and I can‚Äôt wait to open it on Christmas Day and wear a piece of Haida art on my wrist.
If you are lucky and live in Vancouver area, don‚Äôt walk....run on down to Douglas Reynolds and step into a world of First Nation treasures that will delight your eyes and if you‚Äôre lucky, you‚Äôll leave with a beautiful piece(s).
If you live outside the area, their website is super fantastic, easy to navigate, beautiful photos of pieces and they ship anywhere!

Name: Delta Museum
Reviews: [{'author_name': 'Sally Cameron', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/107333661100415806152/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14Gg8QpHbeE1MHH1Pn8lq4YTWq-VQsO3_lzGHnZY=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba2', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': '5 years ago', 'text': "I am so glad that this museum still exists. I used to spend hours here as a child, absorbed in the displays of local BC history and culture. Though the room was nice and the workers were friendly,  I feel that the ceremony was a bit rushed. They did not give the family time to speak on their loss. If it wasn't for the family taking the ceremony into their own hands at the end, we would have only been paying our respects in under 15-20 mins. They need to take into consideration that each and every family that lost a love one needs TIME. Time to heal, grieve, remember,  share, acknowledge, love and thank.  Being able to share stories and reflect among others during the ceremony is a shared and loving time. Taking that moment away from family and friends is not what your company should offer as part of your "package ". They invested thousands of dollars to lay their loved ones to rest and to be rushed is disrespectful.  Also when the attendees was exiting the parking lot, there was no one to direct the traffic. There were cars cutting into the funeral procession because they did not stop the on coming traffic. I remember years ago that funerals where not so rushed. I remember that they actually understood that this was gonna be the last time the family will see their loved ones. Now it's just another day, another dead person, another body to bury , another check.', 'time': 1521039405}]

Name: Inuit Gallery Of Vancouver
Reviews:
[{'author_name': 'Dorian Powell', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/109737767411577343572/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14GhEMPX-IuwI6eFMoSIAORMX2qx1WRteOq82OM1-=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba4', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': '2 months ago', 'text': "My family and I are satisfied customers of the Inuit gallery Vancouver. Not only have they bent over backwards to take care of us, they also work diligently with their artist to make sure their interests are taken care of as well. It's golden an our books when you see both artist and customer at the end of the day happy with the end result..", 'time': 1613163347}, {'author_name': 'Ron Rouben', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/107794604223239361813/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/AATXAJzc3M9rWPNNjQNHFc8gMeBmK0NX4MdF3N3ir_c=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': 'a month ago', 'text': "For those who do not have the time to read the entire review, allow me to front-load the fact that Inuit Gallery of Vancouver exceeded my expectations on all levels.  I most certainly recommend doing business with Melanie and her crew.

I was in the market for a small soapstone sculpture to ship to Montreal for my parents' wedding anniversary and, due to health concerns, could not make it in to the store to shop in-person.  Still, I was extremely motivated to get a gift for my folks and only thanks to the attention and patience and superhuman efforts of the folks at Inuit Gallery of Vancouver did this become possible.  The website makes accessible good quality images, dimensions, and prices of many of the works that are available for purchase.  I had narrowed down my list to 4 or 5 pieces and I needed some guidance to identify the one piece that would ultimately be selected.  Melanie answered questions about sculpture size, quality of the stone used, and even information about the region and the specific artist responsible for the piece.  She did so with great patience and thoughtfulness.  She seemed to understand my needs and wants and helped me to select a piece that absolutely delighted the recipients who already have a good-sized collection accumulated slowly over a great number of years.

Keep in mind that I did not have a large budget, yet despite my inability to afford a much larger piece, Melanie made me feel as if I was the most important client in her Rolodex.  Man Alive, I love when that happens, and it takes a very special person to impart that sense of allegiance to another.

And of course, once we finally selected a particular work, it took me forever to figure out which method of payment I would use and still, Melanie did not flinch.  And, after my interminable bank account gymnastics allowed me to finally complete the purchase, the team did not hesitate to send someone to the post office with the parcel to ensure that it would reach Montreal on time.  WOW!  WOW!  WOW!  WOW!  WOW!

Thank you, Melanie, and Inuit Gallery of Vancouver, for making the impossible happen.  I recognize that I was very high maintenance and that without your commitment to accommodating all of needs, I would not have been able to surprise members of my family with a piece of art that they will treasure for a long time.  Rest up, you will need all of your energy again as I will certainly be calling on you again at the same time next year!
Ron Rouben", 'time': 1617652717}, {'author_name': 'MK - 04GK 828458 Britannia PS', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/100622819724093982030/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14Gichk7TZM7cDbcjPccLS4Fqaehbxsxp6zzTO-ARHA=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo', 'rating': 4, 'relative_time_description': '4 months ago', 'text': 'It is a wonderful place to spend the day at!ü§óüòä', 'time': 1607908385}, {'author_name': 'Tanya Greeno', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/102086180107030759314/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/AATXAJzJ-Z4vLxKFtNApo11L60grNTmpypI2VzSrDBPQ=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': 'a year ago', 'text': 'Great variety of art and prices, staff are knowledgeable and friendly.', 'time': 1587145211}, {'author_name': 'Karen B', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/117106358411695695089/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/AATXAJym1fRqnOJl9pFMBeZqGFqCIvn0W6PpG4T7fvQO=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba5', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': '2 years ago', 'text': "A variety of indigenous art with prices for every budget. Reviews:
[{'author_name': 'Cindy Lee', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/107688525336596583890/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/AATXAJwY98djV_CIJ5K9uLdNBSwbaVF8U394VYhyhGM7=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': '5 months ago', 'text': 'Lovely dinner and drinks!
A girlfriend and I went here early for happy hour and tried the fries, fried chicken, and pizza. Food was pretty good with the fried chicken being the best thing... was so flavourful!
Drinks were awesome and perfectly made.
We tried a small plate of the hand made butternut squash pasta as well and were blown away by the taste - definitely order this one even though it‚Äôs not on the happy hour menu.', 'time': 1607639369}, {'author_name': 'Riley Jackson', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/110106621520147934159/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14GimDr1GfeePLetO4aB70W3drpp8-pKSwbaGc4G7=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': '2 months ago', 'text': 'Top notch for seafood in the Vancouver area. I went here with a group of friends and we arrived on a busy Saturday night. The hostess told us it would be about A 30 minute wait but took us to the bar and found us a seat so that we can go ahead and have a drink While we waited at the bar maybe 15 minutes the host came and checked on us three different times to let us know that our table will be ready soon. I cannot brag on the service enough at this restaurant. Our table order the chef creation a trio of fish the pork chop and the salmon Wellington. They were all cooked to perfection. We also had the calamari and oysters for an appetizer. The lobster oil is a nice surprise with bread and the staff is very conscious of food allergies. This was definitely my favorite dining experience in Vancouver.', 'time': 1613698058}, {'author_name': 'Lili Zwart', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/103748400018033886233/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14GiX9GH7GnnghIJgMKedDQ7uTCpnrXuXWTAl3Fjesg=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': '3 months ago', 'text': 'I come here every time I fly to Vancouver for work. The ambience is gorgeous, alive and swank. The food is crazy good and service top notch. I can‚Äôt believe my bro lives in Port Moody and hasn‚Äôt been. This is a restaurant not to miss. They have fabulous seafood and other menu choices for those who prefer something else. Joe Fortes is an experience not just a meal', 'time': 1611256866}, {'author_name': 'Nicholas Quintillan', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/118017075339925063009/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14Gh8G_TTdwcAzt5YHZu4Tbcp_UXzS_TTONfsGyF1Wg=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba5', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': '2 weeks ago', 'text': 'Joe Fortes is always consistent. The food always arrives exactly as expected (which is a great thing). The aspect I love most about Fortes is that my expectations on food and service are always met with excellence. I always know what to expect having dinner here. Our server ‚ÄòBrian‚Äô (I believe), was particularly exceptional. He was informative, helpful, and a all-around great server. I highly recommend Joe Fortes if you‚Äôre in the mood for traditional seafood. Also, make sure to try the lobster oil. We even bought a bottle for our wedding previously. If you like a classic 30s style venue/restaurant, this is the place to go. Fortes has been a staple of Vancouver for years.', 'time': 1619600977}, {'author_name': 'Justin Kimura', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/116376305484631088803/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14GiJ89MAisc_rxujuR6rnzs9MFxjzBqwx7tvK7XEUQ=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba4', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': 'in the last week', 'text': "One of my go to spots for happy hour or a nice dinner downtown. They are always one of my top choices to recommend for anyone visiting and it's right on Robson, so you can take a nice stroll after to digest. I would have to say if you are planning to come but don't know when to go and love oysters, try their happy hour first.

Parking will be hard to find but once you get there, you will be greeted and brought up to the terrace which is the only thing open during COVID restrictions. Also make sure you book in advance as there will be a wait if you decide to walk in.

This is a great spot especially during the summer as it's a beautiful terrace and elegant ambiance with a delicious happy hour menu. They are known for their oysters so make sure you order tons of them. Great for all occasions, you won't be disappointed. It's just unfortunate the indoor dining is closed at the moment as they usually have a live pianist playing.

Again, I can't say enough good things about this place as I've always left with a great experience. Highly recommend!", 'time': 1620435432}]

[{'author_name': 'Áç®Â≠§Êòé', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/112198363779237080395/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14Gh7TP0DpdOoHiZX4oG8Ba9TQgUgjAdcO46brGDJ=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba6', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': 'a month ago', 'text': "The Morris and Helen Belkin Art Gallery is a contemporary art gallery in Vancouver, British Columbia on the campus of the University of British Columbia. The gallery is housed in an award-winning building designed by architect Peter Cardew and opened in 1995. It houses UBC‚Äôs growing collection of contemporary art as well as an archive containing more than 30,000 objects related to the history of art in Vancouver.

The Morris and Helen Belkin Art Gallery mounts 4 to 7 exhibitions of art per year by nationally and internationally known artists, and works from the collection are showcased annually in a thematic exhibition. The Belkin Art Gallery also creates small scale traveling exhibitions for circulation within Canada, and collaborates on large scale international exhibitions. The gallery's mandate includes research, publication, and a program of screenings, performances, and lectures by artists, scholars, curators and critics.

Since 2003, new outdoor works have been installed on campus by artists Rodney Graham, Jamelie Hassan, Myfanwy Macleod, and Edgar Heap of Birds. A self-guided tour of outdoor art on campus can be downloaded from the Morris and Helen Belkin Art Gallery website. The gallery and campus have outdoor sculpture and have been reported on as part of Vancouver's public art scene. Exhibitions have included artworks by indigenous artists.

Admission to the gallery is free. An estimated 13 percent of the gallery's collection is from female artists and an edit-a-thon was launched at the gallery to create articles on more of those women on Wikipedia in 2017.

The UBC Fine Arts Gallery was founded in 1948 in a basement section of the Main Library on the University campus. The Fine Arts Gallery was the only venue in the Vancouver region that focused exclusively on contemporary art. The gallery rose in national status during the 1960s and 1970s by presenting innovative work by artists who were establishing Vancouver on the international art scene.

Until 1994, the gallery was used only as an exhibition space; afterwards, it began to house and administer the University Art Collection. On June 14, 1995, the Fine Arts Gallery was rededicated as the Morris and Helen Belkin Art Gallery and opened its new facility at 1825 Main Mall.", 'time': 1615778157}, {'author_name': 'Maxwell Chan', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/108736865855698257587/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14Gjicqv0t5oElrvVxfAIs47Cb8iTAdWuxGBbg_QdlPg=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba4', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': 'a week ago', 'text': "a nice, small-ish gallery that's free on campus", 'time': 1620144328}, {'author_name': 'Matthew Hughes', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/114997912129496557882/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/AATXAJx-C5IqZHAgzLtdjpCCQdwWlMhemC97UaQsNcgi=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': 'a year ago', 'text': "A friend visited the gallery last year and saw a book they really wanted but didn't have space for, we bought them the book for Christmas but left it pretty late. The endless trails you can choose from to walk through the park make it the perfect place to go for a morning jog, a meditating walk or a first date. I have so many fond memories in Queen-E, it is a timeless tourist attraction and a local safe haven for anyone who appreciates flowers and nature. Reviews:
[{'author_name': 'Cheryl Stolz', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/101006288178354532100/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14GhDyNyxyIbzpEXQZo6Be-dP-N4q2rsrECLRwMQusw=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo', 'rating': 1, 'relative_time_description': '2 weeks ago', 'text': 'Do not park in their $13.50  "secured" underground parking. The security staff were very unhelpful and wouldn't even help by calling the police or giving us the local police number (as 911 isn't acceptable as it's not an emergency) while we stood out in the dark, rainy night. When we stood in the underground to get out of the rain and to wait on hold for the poIice, security came down right away to tell one of our ladies in our group to extinguish her cigarette immediately. There were no people or cars in the underground at this time as it was around midnight.  I'd like to urge the public to not use this parking lot and not to expect any help if you are in need of any assistance from security on these premises. Reviews:
[{'author_name': 'Dallis Swiatek', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/101231153053544004273/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/AATXAJyjo6kX1OcOsDWSKsswIK32b7H4YmJscKbaHwWo=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba3', 'rating': 2, 'relative_time_description': '3 weeks ago', 'text': 'I STRONGLY warn international students that this program does not provide a post graduate work permit. In the schools advertising they imply that they are providing you with industry connections and fast tracking your career but once you are graduated if you are not a resident Canadian you are on your own and most students end up going back home. International students will likely not find the industry connections they want here if they cannot get a work permit some other way.', 'time': 1618705636}, {'author_name': 'Billy Bob', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/113259991870051738279/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/AATXAJy7EbFIAQiuIonmfNQuKnd9ia3IJxhKN1MDdFce=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo', 'rating': 1, 'relative_time_description': 'a month ago', 'text': "Graduated from the film production program. Myself and everyone I talked to in my class about it agreed that we should have gone to a different film school. It's not worth the money or time. The level of education is so low that they were literally showing No Film School YouTube videos in class.

One person committed suicide while I was there. I know that one of my class mates had a thankfully unsuccessful suicide attempt. Everyone in my class that I talked to about it said their mental health suffered because of the school.

The TA's I talked with all said the school has an increasingly negative reputation in the industry. Some of my class mates got jobs as PA's and said they stopped telling people that they went to VFS because of the reactions they got.

I wish I could get a refund and a year of my life back.", 'time': 1618064053}, {'author_name': 'tenedria', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/108967330590431013422/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14GhzZ-m9t30PRpZHsyG_la9rHZ8Gta5sgfDfpEdRcQ=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba3', 'rating': 2, 'relative_time_description': '4 months ago', 'text': "(game design - >5 years ago)
Overall their handling of learning disabilities is abysmal at best. Hopefully they improved, and no longer stigmatize people with learning disabilities. This was years ago, but my experience there was traumatizing. I must add this treatment is regardless of what your grades are. Even if you have 90-100% they still act like you are failing class.

I'm not giving 1 star because I did learn a lot in the short time I was there. However I went to a different school and they teach the same thing.

Another down side of VFS is that their courses are not individualized. This means if you want to focus on learning 3d modeling, UX design or programming, you won't be able to.

The facilities are better than what other schools have. What a beautiful gallery that I never knew about. It was actually one of the filming locations for Ali Wong's "Always Be My Maybe".

The entire exhibit is food focused, making commentary on how commonplace it is now to take pictures of our food. I'm definitely guilty of this!

Of course, the pieces related to baking and sweets were my favourites! This first one is a collection of baking ingredients for a vintage Ikea ad. Throw in some pieces of processed meats and fruits for good measure!

It was the last of our sunny day streak here, and a perfect opportunity to take a picture of Vancouver from the balcony on the Northshore.

I'd highly recommend going. It's a small exhibit, but it wasn't crowded and admission is by donation. They also have the cutest gift shop.

Follow me on Instagram @vinaeatsandtreats for more honest restaurant, tourism, and baking recipe reviews!', 'time': 1619985900}]

Reviews:
[{'author_name': 'Robert R', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/106791507496093347654/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14GhPpwJvf7DxUIUuceGEouYNZ_NE5ikTAa7TFBJL=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba3', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': 'in the last week', 'text': "The long drive out into deep Langley makes the experience more magical, I love night driving and its about 35mins away along the highway. Name: University of British Columbia: Library Special Collections Division
Reviews:
[{'author_name': 'Áç®Â≠§Êòé', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/112198363779237080395/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14Gh7TP0DpdOoHiZX4oG8Ba9TQgUgjAdcO46brGDJ=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba6', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': 'a month ago', 'text': "The University of British Columbia Library is the library system of the University of British Columbia (UBC). The library is one of the 124 members of the Association of Research Libraries (ARL). In 2017, UBC Library ranked 29th among members of the ARL for the number of volumes in library (physical volumes), making it the third largest Canadian academic library after the University of Toronto and the University of Alberta. However, UBC Library ranked 23rd for the titles held (physical and online documents) and second in Canada, and had a materials expenditures of $13.8 million, placing it 44th.

UBC Library is one of the largest research libraries in Canada, with 13 branches and divisions at UBC and at other locations, including branches at Vancouver Hospital and Health Sciences Centre, and one at the UBC Okanagan campus.

As of 2019, UBC Library's collection comprises 8.3 million items, including 2.8 million e-books, 5.3 million microforms, 440,000 journal titles and more than 923,000 maps, videos and other multimedia materials.[2] During the year 2018/2019, the UBC community downloaded 3.4 million ebooks and 7.4 million journal articles, the equivalent of 89 journal article downloads and 41 ebook downloads per person.

UBC Library has the largest collection of Asian-language materials in North America and the largest biomedical collection in Western Canada. It is a depository library for publications of the governments of British Columbia (BC), Canada, Japan and the United Nations.

The Library's collections of special and unique materials include the archives of Canadian author and artist Douglas Coupland, the Uno Langmann Family Collection of B.C. Photographs (consisting of more than 18,000 rare and unique early photographs of British Columbia), the H. Colin Slim Stravinsky Collection (the largest collection of its kind in Canada, including more than 130 items documenting the work and life of Igor Stravinsky) and the Wallace B. Chung and Madeline H. Chung Collection, containing more than 25,000 rare and one-of-a-kind items relating to the discovery of BC, the development of the Canadian Pacific Railway, and Chinese immigration to Canada. The collection includes documents, books, maps, posters, paintings, photographs, silver, glass, ceramic ware and other artifacts.

In October 2015, UBC Library opened its newest facility, Library Preservation and Archives (PARC), a new modular storage facility designed to accommodate the future growth of library collections. The building is located at UBC Vancouver‚Äôs South Campus (in the Research Precinct) and provides 2,280 square metres of high-density collection storage. It can store about 1.6 million volumes and the facility also houses a campus-wide records management service.", 'time': 1615776711}, {'author_name': 'Mac Luu Ha', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/118411557993284370914/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14GjWJjEILD9hnoU3gw4h4lB8dcTpZbLqxRYygPsUGQ=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba6', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': '7 months ago', 'text': 'Great clock tower, visit this first time back Feb 2015', 'time': 1600644455}, {'author_name': 'Laura Musikanski', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/109378098181800622687/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14GgUbeD7Z9JJlqAkNXD9K6Rsp35R6K3Oj4NL9o2h0Gk=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba8', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': '3 years ago', 'text': 'Such a cool library. After enjoying the art for a while and enjoying paintings of Venice, artifacts, we were welcomed by the owner, one Uno Langmann, who regaled us with history and interesting anecdotes about artists related to his collections.

We look forward to our next visit to the gallery to see the art and enjoy the hospitality and warmth of the family owned and operated gallery.  If you enjoy high caliber traditional artworks, Langmann is a must-see-and-visit establishment to find something as a showcase artwork for your art collection. Reviews:
[{'author_name': 'Ed ser', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/117419397608082211745/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/AATXAJysg_1STbLAPxNtOWfZjCWUFw_WKMKIBpQNaugA=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba4', 'rating': 4, 'relative_time_description': '3 months ago', 'text': 'This place has a very old history about the police in Vancouver. But seeing all the evidence from some of the most famous cases in North American history was well worth it I will definitely be revisiting this exhibit the next time I'm in Vancouver.", 'time': 1612375256}, {'author_name': 'Gary Byrne', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/116367664824086074973/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14Ghy1e-77Kmk-gHSt3TOjZxLy2LvHFnZjPDLFF6Z7Q=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba3', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': 'a month ago', 'text': 'Really cool museum with lots of interesting history. A great way to spend a few hours in the city.', 'time': 1616282097}, {'author_name': 'Áç®Â≠§Êòé', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/112198363779237080395/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14Gh7TP0DpdOoHiZX4oG8Ba9TQgUgjAdcO46brGDJ=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba6', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': 'a month ago', 'text': 'The Vancouver Police Museum (formerly Vancouver Police Centennial Museum) opened to commemorate the centennial of the Vancouver Police Department and the City of Vancouver, British Columbia in 1986. Located at 240 E. Cordova Street in Vancouver's Gastown, the museum is housed in a building that was once both the Coroner‚Äôs Court and autopsy facilities (until 1980) and the City Analyst‚Äôs laboratory (until 1996). In 1935, the Coroner's Court was used as a makeshift hospital by police during the Battle of Ballantyne Pier. It was designed by architect Arthur J. Bird, and today it is a municipally designated heritage building.

The museum is run by the Vancouver Police Historical Society, a non-profit organization established in 1983 with the mandate to foster interest in the history of the Vancouver Police Department and to open a museum for this purpose. The catalyst for the project was the museum's first curator, Joe Swan, a former police sergeant and amateur historian. Swan wrote the department's official history book, which was published by the Vancouver Historical Society in 1986, entitled, A Century of Service: The Vancouver Police, 1886-1986.

The museum houses a collection of approximately 20,000 objects. This includes archival documents, photographs, publications, confiscated firearms and other weapons, counterfeit currency, and various other artifacts and memorabilia, of which an estimated 40% is on display. The museum offers educational programs for children and walking tours of the neighbourhood on the theme, "Sins of the City." The museum has a gift shop and publishes a quarterly newsletter.

The museum is self-funded through admission and program fees, membership fees, donations, gift shop sales, and project grants; the museum receives no direct funding from the Vancouver Police Department or the City of Vancouver but does receive in-kind support.', 'time': 1615773179}, {'author_name': 'Sardor Artikov', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/104033994637462445214/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14Gg29M-9baV2su0p4xto_0MlSus1H2Tq7eb8E9m5OA=s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': 'a week ago', 'text': "Actually a really cool museum! If you're a fan of true crime, confiscated weaponry, and are looking for a place to go for under $20 a head, this is the place for you!", 'time': 1620235700}]
